english:
  title: Epitaph for Minister An Suk, Lord of Chŏngsu, Prime Minister and Judge of the Central Secretariat
  author: Nam Su-mun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the summer following the burial of the Minister who bore the title Chŏngsu and retired in honor, his second son, then serving as Regional Inspector, submitted an account of the Minister's deeds and requested that I compose this epitaph for his tomb. Being bound by kinship and obligation, I could not in conscience refuse.

    According to records, the Minister's given name was Sun, his courtesy name Hyŏnjiji, and he was of the Sunhŭng clan. His great-grandfather was the High Chancellor of Koryŏ, the Lord of Hŭngnyŏng, known as the Sage of Munjeong, whose given name was Ch'uk. He passed the examination under the Yüan court and was known as the Master of the Careful Study. His virtue and learning became the model for his age. When appointed as Censor-General of the eastern region, he compiled the Collection of Tiled Notes, which circulates to this day. His grandfather was the Grand Academician and Minister of State, known as the Sage of Mungan, whose given name was Jongyŏn. His father was the Merit Subject who Aided in Dynastic Founding, known as the Sage of Yangdo, whose given name was Kyŏnggong. His mother was of the Chŏng clan of Ch'ŏngsung, daughter of the Literary Councilor and Lord of Ocho, whose given name was Sado.

    The Minister was born on the eighteenth day of the tenth month of Hongjŭ's fourth year. At age ten, through hereditary privilege, he was appointed Vice-Director of the Court Attendants. At twenty, he passed the civil service examination. At thirty-one, he was enrolled in the Bureau of Ceremonial. At thirty-two, he passed the military examination. The following year he attained the third rank. At thirty-six, he became Lecturer at the National Academy. At thirty-eight, he was made Recorder of the Bureau of Palace Supplies. At thirty-nine, he transferred to the Office of the Censor-General. At forty, he became Vice-Censor and State Historiographer, but when he remonstrated with the throne, he offended the royal will. In the autumn of his forty-second year, he was sent out as magistrate of Kimhae, where his governance was exemplary and the people have mourned him to this day. At forty-three, he was recalled to serve as Junior Official of the Ministry of Rites and Assistant to the Crown Prince.

    In the summer of his forty-four year, he became Regional Director of Kangwŏn Province, and in the autumn took office in the Censor-General's Bureau. When a palace maid transgressed, the Grand Founder commanded the Chief Censor Cho Pyŏk to execute her immediately. Cho informed the Minister, who responded: "The Censor-General's Bureau is not an agency of punishment. Moreover, to execute one without establishing her guilt—is this just?" Cho, citing the royal command, pressed forward. The Minister objected: "Human life is precious beyond measure. Once taken, it cannot be restored. To hastily apply extreme punishment—how can this be reconciled with righteousness? The matter should be submitted to the proper agencies for investigation and judgment." When Cho reported the Minister's words in anger, the Grand Founder, enlightened by his remonstrance, accepted his counsel.

    On another occasion, when the hundred officials were assembled outside the Palace of Auspicious Fortune, seated in ranks to east and west, a certain person of rank rode directly to the inner gate, which no one dared obstruct. The Minister immediately apprehended the rider's attendant and impeached him, whereupon the offender was banished. All praised the Minister's action. The future King Sejong, then Crown Prince, witnessed this incident. After ascending the throne, he repeatedly praised the Minister without ceasing.

    At forty-eight, he became Regional Inspector of the Northwest. At forty-nine, he rose to the rank of Senior Official in the Ministry of War. At fifty, he became Vice-Chancellor of the Bureau of Ranks. At fifty-one, he rose to Senior Court Official, holding multiple offices and bearing the title of Court Attendant. From this time forward, his offices multiplied—he became Censor, Examiner of Punishments, Vice-Minister of the Ranks, Vice-Ministers of Ritual, and repeatedly changed position, all while maintaining his position in the Hall of Scholars. His rank advanced to Counselor of State.

    In the winter of his fifty-five year, he was promoted to Vice-Director of the Chancellor's Secretariat. The following year he advanced to Director, rendering much service to the throne. In winter he transferred to Vice-Minister of Personnel. Shortly after, he became left Vice-Minister. At fifty-seven, he rose to Commander of the Left Army, Compiler of Literati, Director of the Hall of Venerable Literature, and Compiler of the Spring and Autumn Records. In autumn he became Regional Inspector of Kyŏngsang Province. At fifty-nine, he was appointed Commander of the Left Army and Director of the Hall of Venerable Literature. At sixty-two, he became Vice-Governor of Kaesŏng, rising to the title of Superior Court Official. At sixty-four, he was appointed Regional Inspector of Ch'ungch'ŏng Province. At sixty-seven, he became Governor of Kongsan and Director of the Hall of Venerable Literature. In autumn, he was made Vice-Minister of Finance.

    In the winter of his sixty-eight year, he advanced to Minister of Public Works and rose to the title of Counselor of State. At seventy, he mourned his father's death. When Kangwŏn Province suffered famine and many people wandered destitute, the king wished to send a great minister to provide relief, but finding no suitable person, he specially recalled the Minister to appoint him Regional Inspector of that province. Though he declined, necessity compelled compliance. Upon arrival, he gathered the starving people at Hamhŭng and personally supervised their relief, so that the people were saved from death. In winter he requested to retire due to illness, but permission was not granted; instead, he was made Advisor to the State Council.

    At seventy-two, he became Minister of Finance, overseeing the imperial treasury for seventeen years. The budget flourished, expenditures were precise and clear, and not a hair's breadth was unaccounted for. At seventy-five, he rose to the title of Counselor for the Right. At seventy-six, he was made Commandant of the Hall of Justice, serving in this capacity for eight years, conducting trials with generosity and fairness. Once, when a foreign pirate was pursued but not captured, the bureau charged an innocent man living near where a corpse was found. The Minister, taking pity on the injustice, delayed the case and issued a substantial reward, eventually capturing the true criminal and clearing the innocent man's name. The people marveled at his wisdom.

    Another time, a widow was falsely accused of treasonous speech. Interrogated, she would not confess. The magistrate wished to apply torture. The Minister said: "This is a grave matter. How can truth emerge from the torturer's rod? We must bring the accuser and accused face to face and report accordingly to the throne." The king, hearing the Minister's counsel, adopted it, and the widow was freed. The Minister's reversals of injustice were often of this nature.

    At seventy-eight, he rose to the title of Exalted Official. The following year, he was made Director of the Hall of Venerable Literature. At eighty, he became Prime Minister, also retaining his position as Minister of Finance. In the autumn of his eighty-three year, he entered the State Council as Vice-Premier, also Minister of Finance and Director of the Hall of Venerable Literature. In the summer of his eighty-four year, having served out his term, he requested retirement twice and was restored to his position as Prime Minister, his other duties continuing.

    That same year, Ch'ungch'ŏng Province suffered severe famine. The following spring, in the first month, the king, recalling that the Minister had once relieved famine in Kangwŏn Province with good results, appointed him Superintendent of Relief and Provision. When the Minister came to take his leave, the king granted him audience and said: "Generally, a man of talent and virtue can respond to heaven and preserve the people. In ancient times, the Tang Emperor T'aizong earnestly practiced benevolence and righteousness, and within four or five years, the price of rice fell to three coins a measure. I greatly admire this. Since I took the throne, I have striven to govern with care, hoping to bring plenty to the people. Yet year after year have brought floods and droughts. The people go hungry. This failure springs from my lack of virtue. I have spent twenty years in ceaseless self-examination and discipline, hoping for heaven's aid, but to no avail. Now three provinces—Kyŏngsang, Chŏlla, and Ch'ungch'ŏng—suffer disaster, unprecedented in recent times, with Ch'ungch'ŏng most severely afflicted. At such a pass, I cannot hope for heaven's favor. I know not what policies of relief to pursue. Go, and be cautious in your charge." The Minister deployed relief through many channels, and the entire province was saved. In summer, he was granted elevation to the rank of Counselor. At eighty-seven, his original office was changed to that of Director of the Hall of Venerable Literature, and shortly thereafter, claiming illness, he steadfastly declined and was granted retirement.

    When the Minister fell ill, he wrote to his sons saying: "I have reached seventy years; my rank has attained the highest. My descendants are without blemish. Though I die, it is glory. Moreover, life and death follow nature's course. Do not mourn. Let the funeral rites follow family propriety alone; do not commission Buddhist services. People who die bring much activity. I will not let my death burden the living. Let me be buried beside my ancestors' graves to facilitate the arrangements." He then retired to a cottage in Kŭmch'ŏn. The king repeatedly sent imperial physicians and sent meals in succession. On the twenty-eighth day of the eleventh month of his eighty-eight year, he passed away in his chamber.

    When news reached the court, the king was deeply grieved. He suspended audiences for two days, sent envoys to offer condolences and sacrifices, and had the state oversee his funeral arrangements. The following year, in the second month on the third day, he was interred at the ancestral grave north of the county seat, in the valley of Paekksa. The posthumous honors bestowed upon the Minister were indeed without lack.

    The Minister was by nature profound, luminous, modest, and grave. From childhood, he was sparing of speech and laughter. Those who beheld him recognized him as destined for the highest office. He revealed virtue while concealing faults. He was especially generous to his kinsmen. When any among them fell ill or died, even to the humblest servants, he spared no expense in their aid.

    In the year when Councilor Ch'oe Yŏng purged corrupt officials, the Minister's former teacher was implicated and his body cast outside the city walls. When rain caused the corpses to scatter and drift, the Minister, then eighteen, took a single servant and searched for his teacher's remains to give them proper burial. Discerning observers recognized in him the makings of a great minister and anticipated his distinguished future.

    In his household, he spoke not of profit. Sitting alone in stillness, he never set aside his books. He attended to no matters of personal concern. In his official duties, he held firm to rectitude and could not be swayed. When he rose to the rank of Prime Minister, he earnestly upheld the great principles and harbored no love of constant innovation, displaying the bearing of an ancient sage minister.

    When affairs of state required counsel, the king would convene the Three Excellencies for secret deliberation. Only the Minister and the Sage Minister Hŏ Ch'u participated in these consultations.

    He married the Lady Chŏng of Ch'ŏngsung, known as the Worthy Woman Chongsu, daughter of the Literary Councilor and Lord of Ch'ŏngyuan, whose given name was Kŏnggwŏn. She was righteous and quiet, embodying wifely virtue. She predeceased the Minister by six years and was buried in his tomb.

    The Minister fathered four sons. The eldest, Sungdirk, attained the rank of Counselor of State and served twice as magistrate of provinces, both times with benevolent governance. The second, Sungson, rose to the rank of Superior Official and served as Regional Inspector of Kyŏnggi Province. He achieved first place in the examination of the Kyŏngja year and once served as Director of the Silver Terrace. The third, Sungsin, attained the rank of Court Official and served as Vice-Governor of Insun. He died of illness one year after the Minister. The fourth, Sunghyo, attained the rank of Court Official and served as Regional Director of P'yŏngan Province. He too was a man of integrity.

    The Minister had three daughters. The eldest married Yi Sukchi, who attained the rank of Counselor and Vice-Premier of the State Council, serving as Chief Censor and Regional Inspector of three provinces. The second married Cho Hye, who attained the rank of Superior Official and Councilor of the Ministry of Public Works, serving in various offices with reputation for talent. The third married Kim Sunryye, Commissioner of Hyŏnp'ung County and Bearer of the Rank of Court Official.

    The Minister's descendants multiplied, encompassing grandchildren, great-grandchildren, and more, totaling over forty great-grandchildren.

    Observing the families of old that bore great names—how many have within one or two generations ceased to flourish! Yet from the time of the Sage of Munjeong onward, the Minister's line has continuously produced eminent ministers, all bound by loyalty and filial piety, in no way inferior to the four generations and five excellencies of the Yüan family. In their accumulation of merit and virtue, they seem to exceed that precedent. Indeed, when virtue runs deep, its light extends far—this has been verified.

    The Minister's loyal service to the throne and beneficence to the people established such glorious merit that it illuminated his descendants, whose brilliant proliferation scarcely yields to that of the Yüan. The blessings of the An family remain unending.

    Thus the epitaph reads:

    What family bears virtue's gate?
    The An clan by Chukki's streams.
    Who opened their noble source?
    Munjeong the Sage began.

    Their caps bright with office held,
    Generation upon generation their fragrance spread.
    Our Minister alone could carry on,
    In loyalty and diligence performing his part.

    Four reigns did he serve with grace,
    Pouring forth his great benevolence wide.
    Like autumn frost upon the Hall of Censors,
    Like spring warmth in merciful governance shown.

    When people cried out in hunger,
    The Minister brought them life.
    When injustice dwelt in prison's dark,
    The Minister set matters right.

    From benevolence's flowering fullness,
    From wisdom's clarity so bright,
    He served as the throne's support and stay,
    As grace day by day grew light.

    When affairs of state loomed large,
    He was consulted for the final word.
    In age he set aside his rank,
    As mountains grew green and waters clear.

    In wealth and years he was blessed,
    From beginning unto end with honor crowned.
    Among all who held high station,
    Who matched his dignity and renown?

    Much more his worthy sons,
    Who inherit their father's virtue great.
    Chukki's waters flow forever,
    Spreading blessings without end.

    There by the streams of Kŭmch'ŏn,
    Lies his chamber in the earth.
    This stone marks it for all ages—
    A monument towering high.
